BNP, British Sky, Infineon: European Equity Preview

-- B y   W h i t n e y   K i s l i n g
-- 
2011-05-10T11:04:17Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-10/bnp-british-sky-infineon-european-equity-preview-correct-.html
(Corrects to remove misspelling of JCDecaux from headline)  The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index fell 0.3 percent to 280.43. The
Stoxx 50 Index declined 0.5 percent to 2,627.28. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, dropped 1.7
percent to 2,902.40.  BNP Paribas (BNP)  : The company plans to announce at the
annual shareholder meeting on May 11 that Chairman Michel Pebereau will retire by next year and be replaced by Chief
Executive Officer Baudoin Prot, the Financial Times reported,
without saying where it got the information. Deputy CEO Jean- Laurent Bonnafe will succeed Prot, the newspaper reported. The
stock fell 2.7 percent to 52.94 euros.  British Sky Broadcasting Group Plc (BSY)  : The U.K.’s
biggest pay-television provider asked an appeals court to
reverse a regulator’s “dramatic intervention” limiting how
much it can charge rivals for coverage of soccer matches. The
shares were unchanged at 839 pence.  Cofinimmo (COFB)  SA:  Belgium ’s largest real-estate
investment fund bought five nursing homes from Dexia Immorent NV
for 47 million euros ($67 million). Cofinimmo shares lost 0.9
percent to 95.36 euros.  Infineon Technologies AG (IFX)  : Europe’s second-largest
chipmaker said it plans to return up to 300 million euros ($429
million) of capital to investors until March 2013, according to
a statement. The company may buy back up to 40 million shares,
it said. Infineon shares climbed 1.1 percent to 8 euros.  JCDecaux SA (DEC)  : The world’s second-largest seller of
outdoor advertising had first-quarter revenue of 535.3 million
euros, compared with 487.2 million euros a year earlier, the
company said in an e-mailed statement. Shares rose 1.2 percent
to 23.15 euros.  Solvay SA (SOLB)  : The world’s largest soda-ash maker
said first-quarter earnings before interest, tax and special
items from continuing operations rose 79 percent to 197 million
euros, beating analysts’ estimates. Solvay shares increased 1.1
percent to 99.96 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Whitney Kisling in New York at 
 wkisling@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at   nbaker7@bloomberg.net  